Question:
\begin{problem}
A pile of coconuts is to be shared by five castaways.  
During each of \emph{five} consecutive night–time turns, a different castaway performs the following procedure:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The castaway divides the current pile into $5$ equal whole–number piles and finds exactly $1$ coconut left over.
    \item The extra coconut is discarded (it is \emph{not} returned to the pile).
    \item The castaway hides one of the five equal piles for himself.
    \item The remaining four equal piles are pushed together to form the next pile.
\end{enumerate}

After all five castaways have taken a turn in this way, the pile that remains in the morning is divided equally among the five castaways with \emph{no} remainder.

What is the least possible positive integer number of coconuts that could have been in the original pile?
\end{problem}

